<?php
namespace App\Http\Controllers;

class ResourceController extends Controller
{
    private $guides = [
        'how-to-choose-rehab' => ['title' => 'How to Choose a Rehab Center', 'meta_title' => 'How to Choose the Right Rehab Center | RehabFlow', 'meta_desc' => 'A step-by-step guide to finding the right rehab facility. Accreditation, staff, programs, insurance, and what to ask.', 'content' => 'Choosing a rehabilitation center is one of the most important decisions in the recovery journey. This guide walks you through the essential factors to consider.', 'sections' => [['heading' => 'Check Accreditation', 'text' => 'Look for JCAHO (Joint Commission) or CARF accreditation. These certifications mean the facility meets national quality standards for care. Accredited centers undergo rigorous review processes and maintain high standards.'], ['heading' => 'Verify Staff Credentials', 'text' => 'Ensure the center employs licensed therapists, certified addiction counselors, medical doctors, and psychiatric professionals. Ask about staff-to-patient ratios — lower ratios mean more personalized attention.'], ['heading' => 'Understand Treatment Approaches', 'text' => 'Evidence-based therapies like CBT, DBT, and motivational interviewing should be the foundation. Be cautious of programs that rely solely on one approach. The best centers use individualized, multi-modal treatment plans.'], ['heading' => 'Check Insurance and Costs', 'text' => 'Verify that the facility accepts your insurance before enrolling. Ask about out-of-pocket costs, sliding-scale options, and payment plans. Understand the total cost including medications and aftercare.'], ['heading' => 'Evaluate Location and Environment', 'text' => 'Consider whether proximity to home is beneficial (family involvement) or risky (access to triggers). Some people thrive in out-of-state programs that provide a fresh start.'], ['heading' => 'Ask About Aftercare Planning', 'text' => 'Recovery does not end at discharge. Strong programs build aftercare plans including outpatient therapy, support groups, sober living, and alumni networks. Ask specifically what happens after treatment ends.']]],
        'what-to-expect-in-rehab' => ['title' => 'What to Expect in Rehab', 'meta_title' => 'What to Expect in Rehabilitation Treatment | RehabFlow', 'meta_desc' => 'A detailed guide to what happens during rehab: intake, detox, therapy, daily routine, and discharge planning.', 'content' => 'Going to rehab can feel overwhelming. Knowing what to expect can help reduce anxiety and prepare you for a transformative experience.', 'sections' => [['heading' => 'The Intake Process', 'text' => 'On day one, you will complete a comprehensive assessment including medical history, substance use history, mental health screening, and insurance verification. The clinical team creates a personalized treatment plan based on your needs.'], ['heading' => 'Medical Detox (If Needed)', 'text' => 'If you are physically dependent, detox is the first step. Medical staff monitor your vitals, manage withdrawal symptoms with medications, and keep you safe and comfortable. Detox typically lasts 3-10 days.'], ['heading' => 'A Typical Day in Rehab', 'text' => 'Days are structured: wake up, breakfast, morning group therapy, individual counseling, lunch, educational workshops, recreational activities, evening group, personal time, and lights out. Structure helps rebuild healthy routines.'], ['heading' => 'Types of Therapy', 'text' => 'You will participate in individual therapy (1-on-1 with a counselor), group therapy (peer sharing and learning), family therapy (rebuilding relationships), and potentially holistic therapies like yoga, meditation, or art therapy.'], ['heading' => 'Rules and Expectations', 'text' => 'Most facilities have rules: no drugs/alcohol, no violence, mandatory attendance, limited phone access (especially early on), and curfews. These boundaries create a safe recovery environment.'], ['heading' => 'Discharge and Aftercare', 'text' => 'Before leaving, your team creates an aftercare plan: outpatient therapy, support groups, sober living options, medication management, and emergency contacts. The transition plan is critical for long-term success.']]],
        'paying-for-treatment' => ['title' => 'Paying for Addiction Treatment', 'meta_title' => 'How to Pay for Rehab: Insurance, Financing & Free Options | RehabFlow', 'meta_desc' => 'Learn how to pay for rehab: insurance coverage, Medicaid, financing, scholarships, state-funded programs, and free treatment options.', 'content' => 'Cost should never be a barrier to treatment. There are many ways to fund rehabilitation, from insurance to free programs.', 'sections' => [['heading' => 'Insurance Coverage', 'text' => 'Under the Mental Health Parity and Addiction Equity Act and the ACA, most insurance plans must cover substance abuse treatment at the same level as medical/surgical care. Contact your insurer to verify specific benefits.'], ['heading' => 'Medicaid', 'text' => 'Medicaid covers addiction treatment for low-income individuals. In expansion states, single adults earning up to 138% of the federal poverty level qualify. Coverage includes detox, residential, outpatient, and MAT.'], ['heading' => 'State-Funded Programs', 'text' => 'Every state operates substance abuse treatment programs funded through SAMHSA block grants. These programs serve uninsured and underinsured individuals. Wait lists may apply — call SAMHSA at 1-800-662-4357.'], ['heading' => 'Sliding-Scale Fees', 'text' => 'Many treatment centers offer sliding-scale fees based on income. This means your cost is adjusted to what you can reasonably afford. Always ask about financial assistance during the intake process.'], ['heading' => 'Financing and Payment Plans', 'text' => 'Some facilities offer payment plans, healthcare financing (CareCredit, Prosper Healthcare Lending), or accept credit cards. Break the total cost into manageable monthly payments.'], ['heading' => 'Scholarships and Grants', 'text' => 'Some nonprofits and treatment centers offer scholarships for those who cannot afford care. The SAMHSA helpline can connect you with local free or low-cost options.']]],
        'family-guide' => ['title' => 'Family Guide to Addiction & Recovery', 'meta_title' => 'Family Guide: Supporting a Loved One in Recovery | RehabFlow', 'meta_desc' => 'How to support a loved one through addiction and recovery. Setting boundaries, intervention, family therapy, and self-care.', 'content' => 'Addiction affects the entire family. This guide helps you understand how to support your loved one while protecting your own well-being.', 'sections' => [['heading' => 'Understanding Addiction as a Disease', 'text' => 'Addiction is a chronic brain disease, not a moral failing. The brain changes caused by substances make it extremely difficult to stop without help. Understanding this helps replace blame with compassion.'], ['heading' => 'Setting Healthy Boundaries', 'text' => 'Boundaries protect you while still showing love. Examples: "I will not give you money for substances" and "I will not cover for your behavior." Boundaries are not punishment — they are self-care.'], ['heading' => 'How to Talk About Treatment', 'text' => 'Choose a calm moment (not during intoxication). Express concern with "I" statements: "I worry about your health." Offer specific help: "I found a program that accepts your insurance — can we call together?"'], ['heading' => 'Professional Intervention', 'text' => 'If direct conversations are not working, a professional interventionist can facilitate a structured, loving conversation. Interventions have a 80-90% success rate in getting the person to accept treatment.'], ['heading' => 'Family Therapy During Treatment', 'text' => 'Many programs include family therapy sessions to heal relationships, improve communication, and address enabling patterns. Participating in family programming significantly improves long-term outcomes.'], ['heading' => 'Taking Care of Yourself', 'text' => 'Join Al-Anon or Nar-Anon support groups. Consider individual therapy. You cannot help someone else if you are depleted. Your well-being matters too.']]],
        'relapse-prevention' => ['title' => 'Relapse Prevention Guide', 'meta_title' => 'Relapse Prevention Strategies & Warning Signs | RehabFlow', 'meta_desc' => 'Learn relapse prevention strategies, warning signs, and how to build a sustainable recovery plan. Evidence-based approaches for long-term sobriety.', 'content' => 'Relapse is not failure — it is a common part of recovery. Understanding the process and building prevention strategies is essential for long-term sobriety.', 'sections' => [['heading' => 'Understanding Relapse as a Process', 'text' => 'Relapse happens in three stages: emotional (isolation, poor self-care), mental (romanticizing use, bargaining), and physical (actual use). Recognizing early stages allows intervention before substance use occurs.'], ['heading' => 'Identify Your Triggers', 'text' => 'Common triggers: stress, emotional pain, social situations, certain people or places, boredom, overconfidence, and life transitions. Create a written list of your personal triggers and plan how to handle each one.'], ['heading' => 'Build a Support Network', 'text' => 'Recovery is not a solo journey. Attend support groups (AA, NA, SMART Recovery), maintain a relationship with a sponsor or recovery coach, and stay connected to sober friends and family.'], ['heading' => 'Develop Healthy Routines', 'text' => 'Exercise, proper nutrition, adequate sleep, and stress management are foundational. Replace substance use with positive activities: hobbies, volunteering, sports, creative expression.'], ['heading' => 'Create a Relapse Prevention Plan', 'text' => 'Write down: your triggers, coping strategies, emergency contacts, reasons for staying sober, and steps to take if cravings occur. Keep this plan accessible and review it regularly.'], ['heading' => 'What to Do If Relapse Occurs', 'text' => 'Seek help immediately — call your sponsor, therapist, or helpline. Do not let shame prevent you from reaching out. Adjust your treatment plan and consider increasing support (more meetings, outpatient sessions, or residential care).']]],
    ];

    public function index() { return view('resources.index', ['guides' => $this->guides]); }
    public function show($slug) {
        if (!isset($this->guides[$slug])) abort(404);
        return view('resources.show', ['guide' => $this->guides[$slug], 'slug' => $slug, 'allGuides' => $this->guides]);
    }
}